segments.text: Everybody's built that bonfire that year.
I'll show you these pictures of the bonfire of 48.
It was an upper-class privilege to work on the bonfire.
Freshmen could guard it, but they could not work on the bonfire because that was an upper-class privilege.
But could freshmen help cut out in the cut area?
No.
We were not, or at least I don't know of anyone who went out there.
We would build our little campfires around the bonfire, and we would guard it to keep anybody from sneaking in there and setting it off.
About how long did the work on the bonfire last?
About how many weeks?
Oh, I would say at least for possibly six weeks.
And the, so the upperclassmen, I'm using sophomores now as an upperclassman, they're the ones that did the cutting and the hauling.
Yes.
And it was, Bonfire was erected on the drill field.
On the drill field.
Up in the corner opposite the YMCA.
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
And it was one log height that was not a double stack.
It was a teepee style as you see in these pictures.
We had a center pole which was actually two telephone poles lashed together and set in the ground six or eight feet.
Were there any pranks or anything by anybody to try to
Did anybody try to set it off on fire or anything like that?
Very definitely.
In the fall of 48, we were 0 and 9 going into the Texas game.
One afternoon during English class, we were up on the third floor of the academic building.
The windows were open, and we heard this airplane noise.
And we looked out.
and had a perfect view of the drill field.
And here came this light airplane in a slight dive.
And the door opened on the airplane and out tumbled this silvery looking thing, which turned out to be a five gallon can of gas with a rag wick stuffed in it.
And these guys had lit that thing in the airplane
and kicked it out.
And they missed by a good margin.
And by the time the can of gasoline, five gallon can, hit the ground, it put the wick out and gasoline went all over the ground and nothing caught.
Well, they came back around and tried it again.
And this time, we were able to get the NC number
the registration number off the underside of the wing.
And somebody, I don't remember who it was, went to one of the professor's offices and called Easterwood Tower and gave them the number on the wing.
And they put that on the CAA wire and it went to all airports in the area.
And this particular airplane, to no one's surprise, came out of Austin.
By the time they landed back at Robert Miller Airport, they had a delegation out there to meet them.
I don't know whatever happened to them, but I'm sure they got in a lot of trouble.
And they weren't Aggies.
They were not Aggies.
I mean, the people meeting them, they were in federal trouble.
Oh, they were in federal trouble, all kinds of trouble.
Let's go back now, football season.
Describe what it was like for a fish to go to Aggie football games.
It was a highlight, the social highlight.
Everything revolved around athletics.
Your social life revolved around athletics, with the exception of an occasional ballman row dance or Bob Hope coming to town with Les Brown and his band right now.
The social activity revolved around football games.
And those of us who had dates,
I was still unmarried during the football season.
Our dates would come up, and we'd make arrangements for them to live at professors' houses, or those of us who could afford it would put them up at the Aggieland Inn.
Did you do that even as a freshman?
Yeah.
Oh, sure.
Is a freshman privileged to have a date?
And the better looking, the better.
Do you have any idea, what did an overnight fee cost at the Aggieland Inn or the faculty member's home?
Well, the faculty member's home was nothing.
And at the Aggieland Inn, I don't know, I think it was
Eight or nine bucks, something like that.
Big money for that.
You saved up all season for that.
Now you were, you had this very important young lady from high school that you had known?
Yes, I did.
She was my high school sweetheart.
She came to games even when your freshman year?
Yes, my folks would bring her to games.
And they would either drive back after the game or
my folks and she would stay at the Andersons' home as their guests.
All right, for you as a fish, was there a march-in in those days of the Corps?
Oh yeah, couldn't get out of that.
We had march-ins just like you do today.
And then how did you meet her in the stands?
Did y'all have previously agreed upon place?
Yes, we did.
Because the student section, there was no reserved seating.
And I'd say, why don't you sit around the 20 or 30 yard line?
You know, fish in those days, you had to sit down low and you had to sit down near the goal line.
And I would say, get as far up to the 20 yard line as you can.
And when we're dismissed, I'll meet you there.
And do you remember any important football game events or experiences?
There was nearly always a dance before the game on Friday night.
In Sabisa?
Well, the big dances would be on Saturday night, of course, after the game.
At Sabisa?
At Sabisa.
Sabisa was...
That was a place where if you were going to have an orchestra, and usually we would have Aggieland orchestra, which was very good, by the way.
When there was a dance after the game, or any other big dance, what did a young man and a young woman wear to Aggie dances then?
We wore our uniforms.
And what did they wear?
The young ladies wore suitable dresses.
They were not formal dances.
The only time we had formal dances was when we would have big bands, like Vaughn Monroe, Les Brown.
Then it would be formal.
Or the ring dance, or the...
Boot dance.
The boot dance, and... Cotton ball.
Cotton ball, sweetheart ball, the big balls.
How did Aggies and their dates behave at those dances?
Just as...
the Sunday school crowd would have been proud of us.
Now, did anybody, that's the answer I expected.
I was at the dance.
Yeah.
But did anybody tell you as a fish or at any other time how you were supposed to behave?
Or did you, did everybody just understand that?
Yeah, we just understood.
And you palled around at a dance.
You palled around with upperclassmen.
Mm-hmm.
And
Of course, the athletes were a pretty close-knit group to begin with.
And we would, our sport would get a table.
We'd have all track people.
Football guys would have two or three football tables.
And we'd intermingle like that.
And we'd dance with each other's dates.
And we'd just have a big time.
Now, did you and your track buddies, did you all feel that you were truly part of the student body and accepted by them?
Oh, absolutely.
That's the answer I expected.
Absolutely.
In fact, we were put up on a slight pedestal.
Not too high, you understand, because you don't want to fish to get a big head.
But we were pretty well thought of, I'll put it that way.
And did you go on a core trip your freshman year?
Yes, I went on a core trip to Austin.
What was that like?
Well, it was pretty inspiring for me and some of my fish buddies because we were 09 when we went down to Austin and we just had to figure out some way
to make the TSIPs pay if we couldn't beat them.
So some of the agronomy students told some of the fish students, look, we've got this new hybrid ryegrass seed, guaranteed to sprout.
All it needs is a little water.
So we got, I don't know, 200 or 300 pounds of that and sneaked into Memorial Stadium in the dark of night.
about the second week of September.
Now, who is we?
I mean, November.
Who is we?
Who is we?
Probably the same bunch of us that stole the outhouse.
Billy Bless, Don Graves, Marshall Sorrell, me, Jody Zurn.
One car load?
Two car loads.
Two car loads.
Actually, a car load and pickup truck load because we had to carry the grass seed down there.
Anyhow, we snuck into Memorial Stadium.
How'd you get into the stadium?
We just climbed over the gate.
Okay.
There were no guards.
Yeah, yeah.
No guards.
And if we couldn't have got in through the gate, we'd have scaled the wall.
It was nothing for us.
We were athletes.
And we, from goal line to goal line, we put a big A, M.
Fifty yards to the letter.
And the greenskeepers were very accommodating there at Austin, and they kept the field watered.
As luck would have it, about a week before Thanksgiving, we had a good hard freeze, which killed the Bermuda.
Oh, oh, oh.
This was hybrid ryegrass.
Didn't harm the ryegrass.
That, all that water that they had been putting on there stimulated it.
And with the Bermuda turning brown, the ryegrass just stood out green.
And there it was.
Did anybody here officially know who had done that?
Oh, no.
No.
Absolutely not.
Did, did.
Their lips were sealed.
And how long was it before that secret got out?
As to who?
Oh, nobody ever knew.
Is that right?
Is that right?
Nobody, at least nobody ever admitted it.
And I presume it was in the paper.
It was in the paper.
It was in the, the bat had a big story on it in the Austin paper.
Y'all left here about what time of night to go there and do it?
Oh, we left here around, I don't know, 9 o'clock.
Got down there about 11 or 11.30.
And we were
back in our bunks by two.
And Colonel Boatner never asked for the guilty party to step forward, which surprised us.
And I don't know what we would have done if he had made that demand.
I think we would have taken the tack that
He's just doing this to go through the motions.
He doesn't really expect anybody to step forward.
Now, as far as you remember, whose idea was it?
Who thought it up?
I have no idea.
Somebody just proposed it in a late-night bull session.
And how did y'all pay for the seed?
We didn't.
The senior agronomy students made it available.
That's what I was going to say.
It just happened to come out.
It was made available.
Okay, okay.
But that senior did not go with y'all to, was it all fish that did the scattering?
It was all fish.
The same dirty half dozen.
And so what did you and your buddies do when you went to the game and looked at it?
We just
We just slapped each other on the back, and everybody said, that's good bull.
Now, you went over there for the Corps trip, and you marched down Congress.
Marched up Congress Avenue.
How did you and your buddies feel being part of the Corps marching like that?
We were damn proud.
Damn proud.
Now, did the crowd standing on the curbs, did they respond positively?
Very positively.
All right.
Now, there's another one.
In all these interviews, when I've asked that question, nobody yet has offered any bad, you know, somebody said something or threw something or was an
Everybody says, no, no, no.
They were always very respectful.
Now, I presume, and the game, unfortunately, did not come out favorably for the Aggies.
Well, it did if you look on a tie as a favorable outcome, especially since we were about four touchdowns underdog.
We tied them 14-14, and we scored from scrimmage.
toward South Gold.
That's right, that's right.
So you go home Christmas.
How did you feel about being an Aggie and academically, how did you feel that you were doing here?
We had gotten our midterm grade reports, I don't know, I guess first part of November, and those of us who did well felt quite proud.
turned in all A's that first semester.
I didn't find it as challenging as high school, to tell you the truth.
And were you already, you were already working out for track?
Colonel Andy says everybody will hit the cross-country course.
Shot putters, discus throwers, high jumpers, sprinters, hurdlers, distance men, everybody went out on the cross-country course.
which started on the west side of the track opposite the old depot where the old creamery was.
And we went clockwise around the course.
And all it was was an old gravel road.
It was hazardous because it had rocks on it the size of double fists.
But Colonel Andy insisted that everybody go out there and do it.
And that road happened to go through the pig farm where George Bush Library now stands.
I don't know if he knows that or not.
But those of us who were not cross-country inclined found shortcuts that after we'd get down there a quarter of a mile or so, and we would cut across.
And we would sit out in the middle of the pasture out there, allow a suitable amount of time to go by, and then we would go finish the rest of the course.
Of course, I'm sure it wasn't any secret to Colonel Andy what we were doing.
But it was really hazardous, because a lot of guys would turn their ankles on those rocks.
And I think he kind of weaned himself off of that in later years.
Now, A&M wasn't doing indoor track then.
There wasn't, was it?
No, there was no indoor track.
That's what I thought.
So you go home Christmas looking forward to the spring, and that special young lady was there.
And did you feel that you'd made a good choice about where to go to college and all?
Were you feeling good about being an Aggie?
I felt good about being an Aggie.
Excuse me, but I was having a little problem on the home front there because she was enrolled at Lamar.
It was a junior college at that time.
And her folks were making noises about sending her to Austin, Texas University.
And we talked this over and I said, hey, that's not gonna work.
You know, I can't be running down there to Austin, and I can hitchhike, but you don't have a car, and you won't be able to come up to College Station unless you find somebody who does.
And you're going to be down there with all those frat rats, and I don't know how this is going to work out.
And she said, well, don't worry about it.
Well, I was worried about it, because she was a very popular girl.
She was a class favorite.
class beauty and all this kind of stuff.
And I had made inquiries to some of the assistant coaches at Texas since I hadn't run into track meet with the maroon and white yet, if their offer of a scholarship was still open.
And they said, yes, it was.

Just to show you what integrity there was among coaches in those days, Clyde Littlefield called me and he said, yes, your scholarship is still open, but have you thought this over and have you talked to Colonel Andy?
I said, no, I have not talked to him yet because I didn't feel there was any point in talking to him until I found out whether you had a place for me.
There were no limits on scholarships in those days.
And he said, yes, it's still open, but I'd advise you to talk to Colonel Andy.
I said, yes, I'll do that.
Well, the next thing I knew, the next day, bright and early, Colonel Andy was at my dorm room before I went to breakfast.
Clyde Littlefield had called him the night before and said, I need to tell you this.
And they were great friends.
And so he came up to see me and asked me what was wrong.
And I said, my girl is going to go to Texas.
And I can see me just losing out big time.
And he said, well, we've got to try to work something out.
I said, I'm working on it currently, Andy.
I'm working on it.
So at midterm, my fish year.
I just said, hey, I'm getting more worried by the minute, and I'm not able to concentrate and work out properly and study properly.
Let's get married.
So we did.
We borrowed her folks' car and went to Cone Springs in San Jacinto County and got a Methodist minister out of bed and got him to marry us.
And then we went back home and told our folks.
Did they both approve?
Didn't have much choice.
It was a fait accompli.
All right, and that's at midterm?
Midterm.
Okay.
And so then did you, did she come up here?
Not right away.
Okay.
Because there was just no place.
Right.
There were a lot of veterans who had taken up all the available housing.
There were no apartments.
The kind of thing that you see today just didn't exist.
Before you got married that fall, how did you and she communicate?
Phone calls, letters, what?
Letters.
Phone calls were too expensive.
Three cents.
About how often?
Oh, two or three times a week.
And did your folks call you?
No, there was no place they could call.
Hart Hall didn't have a telephone.
Did you write back and forth to your parents?
Wrote back and forth.
Did your mom send some kush?
She sent kush.
She sent fish packages, we called them.
And of course, I would go home about maybe two weekends
a month.
You recall my roommate had a car, and he was in Beaumont.
And we'd go home at least once a month, and perhaps I would hitchhike the other weekend.
So I was home a couple times a month.
Alright, so that second semester your freshman year, you're married, but your wife's still in Beaumont.
And what effect does those realities have on your academic and athletic efforts that spring?
I made all A's again.
And the work wasn't that tough, to tell you the truth.
And I was undefeated.
my freshman year.
And you ran both hurdles?
Ran both hurdles.
Did you run a relay also?
I ran mile relay and sprint relay.
What was it, for you as a hurdler, what was it like, the difference between the height of the high school and the college high hurdles?
Was that a tough adjustment?
Not for me.
Some of the guys coming out of high school
had trouble adjusting to the highs.
Billy Bless, for example, had trouble adjusting to the highs.

He was a little gun-shy because he would hit his left knee on the hurdle, and he bloodied and bruised his left knee up pretty high, which as a consequence would force him to go to the hurdles even higher.
Of course, if you do that, the more time you spend in the air means less time spent on the ground running.
I was fortunate enough that I could get over.
There was just a three-inch difference, and after a couple of weeks, it didn't make that much difference to me.
Describe your practice routine once the weather gets warm enough where you can really work out consistently outside.
I would usually start out with a lap or two to warm up
This is all inside Kyle Field?
Inside Kyle Field.
It's the only track we had.
We would run the straightaways and jog the curves.
We'd do that for a couple of three laps and then we would go practice a few starts and we'd put up the hurdles and run through say half a flight of hurdles and about twice a week
we'd run competition with a full flight of hurdles, both high and low.
And you worked out about how long?
We'd work out about two hours, two and a half hours.
When in the afternoon was that?
Generally from, we would arrange our schedule and the profs in the registrar were very accommodating.
They'd let us terminate our classes around
2 to 3 o'clock, unless you had a lab-type class in the afternoon.
Then you might not get out till 4.
And we'd get out there about 3, work out till about 5.30.
Describe Coach Andy as a coach at practice.
What did he do and not do?
What was his routine?
Colonel Andy was kind of a low-key type coach.
He was not a lot of hands-on.
Colonel Andy and Ray Putnam, they were the coaches.
Ray Putnam handled quarter milers and above in terms of distance.
Colonel Andy handled sprinters, hurdlers, and field event men.
And he'd spend quite a bit of time with the field event people.
And he would work with us on our starts, particularly.
and he left me pretty much alone on the hurdles because I guess he figured I had learned all the technique I was going to learn at that stage of the game and he wasn't going to mess with it.
He from time to time would say have you tried this or could you get your lead arm down a little bit lower or something like that and that was about it.
Now did you have a model

hurdler that was your your uh idol your no no i didn't um i knew about guys like freddie walcott who set the world record at 13-7 but you i'd never met him i'd never seen him run you had no movies of people in those days you had still photos and
You really had nothing to learn from.
And did you have a goal that first year of time or anything?
No, I had no goal other than just to run as hard and as fast as I could, as often as I could.
Now, in the Southwest Conference in those days, the Aggies and the Longhorns were the two best teams.
Weren't they in track?
So was Rice.
Rice was right up there.
Oh, that's right.
That's right.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Who was coaching Rice then?
One of the football coaches, if I'm not mistaken.
Yeah.
Rice had Augie Erfer.
Yeah, yeah.
Tobin wrote.
They had Red Brown, Otha Bird, Bill Houghton.
Tommy Cox.
Don't forget Tommy Cox.
And there were freshman meets then.
When, what was your, do you remember your first meet as a college student?
I remember it very clearly.
Where?
The first meet we had was a triangular meet with North Texas and
John Tarleton.
John Tarleton ran against the Fish.
They were in junior college.
And even at the big meets, junior college Fish would always run together.
And I remember that John Tarleton had a hurdler and North Texas had a hurdler.
